<h2>The Beginning</h2>

<p>Just think, the universe burst into being. It didn’t exist, and then suddenly there it was. It burst forth, from possibly, absolutely nothing, and then out spilled a dense concoction of the foundations of our lives.</p>

<p>It’s said that in during the birth of this universe, in the early, tiny fractions of seconds of its existence, it grew so monumentally fast and so incomprehensibly huge, that our human brains couldn’t comprehend it.</p>

<p>The growth would be like something the size of a small molecule, expanding past the confines of our planet, out of our solar system, and reaching past Sirius, the brightest star in our night sky.
</p>

<p>During this time, the laws of physics that we have now, like gravity, came into being too. Had the universe not gone the way it did, our gravity might be widely different, and who we are now wouldn’t have been possible.
</p>

<p>For the next, hundreds of thousands of years, the universe would have developed the first infant stages of light and matter. Little specks, so incredibly tiny, that only the machines we build can detect them.
</p>

<p>And then it grew stars and galaxies…
</p>

