<h2>Our changing stardust</h2>

<p>Our planet has been around for just over 4 billion years. A part of the stardust that formed the Earth, accumulated into a life-form. A little cell, which was around 10 to 100 times smaller than a human hair.
</p>

<p>This cell lived. It made another. Which made another, and another, and another. Eventually these cells came together, and formed a multicellular being, which grew and lived, and made another. An un-breaking chain of life.
</p>

<p>We went from cells to full mammalian creatures, to apes, to humans. Eventually you were born, as was I. And like all those before us, at some point we won't be here too. But then new life will come. And one day, in a very distant future, our Earth will be swallowed by our star, and what new things will come from that we will never know.
</p>

<p>Our universe is in perpetual motion. A cycle where the end of one thing, creates the start of another. Stars are made, they burn and create, and then they die, giving life to more stars, or planets.
</p>

<p>We live by taking in plants (or animals that eat plants if you’re that way inclined), we take in water from the seas and clouds, and one day we’ll all go back to it.
</p>

<p>The beautiful things that made us, and that we enjoyed seeing and being in and of, we will become. We’ll be in the clouds and in the water, and we’ll be in the trees.
</p>

<p>So let’s enjoy what we can, in this time we have now.</p>

<p>And when you are feeling down, remember, you are made of stardust.</p>

